            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="40"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14337336' href='vote?id=14337336&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14331752'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=gajjanag" class="hnuser">gajjanag</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14337336">39 minutes ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14337336"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="1" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14337336)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">This is an astute observation.<p>The world leaders during WW2 recognized this - basically, when critical work needed to be done, they knew whom they needed and roped in a large number of the leading &quot;dreamers&#x2F;thinkers&quot; of the time to work on the Manhattan Project.<p>The thing that saddens me is that it is often conflict and animosity that awaken this recognition - other examples include the Cold War, artillery calculations in WW1, etc.<span>
